    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If we don’t handle this problem, we’ll end up creating bad training data. We need to fix this so that we don’t accidentally teach the machine to recognize those two squashed-together letters as one letter.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A simple hack here is to say that if a single contour area is a lot wider than it is tall, that means we probably have two letters squished together. In that case, we can just split the conjoined letter in half down the middle and treat it as two separate letters:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
