750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*ehE02z5AzBv1zt3UExB2_w.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*ehE02z5AzBv1zt3UExB2_w.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*ehE02z5AzBv1zt3UExB2_w.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1000/1*ehE02z5AzBv1zt3UExB2_w.png 1000w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/500/1*ehE02z5AzBv1zt3UExB2_w.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">We’ll split any regions that are much wider than they are tall in half and treat it as two letters. It’s hacky, but it works fine for these CAPTCHAs.</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now that we have a way to extract individual letters, let’s run it across all the CAPTCHA images we have. The goal is to collect different variations of each letter. We can save each letter in it’s own folder to keep things organized.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
